passages.text: August 29, 2025 07:12 AM GMT

Despite the lower US terminal rate pricing after dovish Fed communication post- Jackson Hole, USD/JPY has been traded resilient around 14.7.00. We see the risk of USD/JPY going significantly lower if incoming US data continue to show the softness. Stay short USD/JPY.

While USD/JPY fair value dropped to 141 due to lower US terminal rate pricing, the actual USD/JPY has been range- bound around the 14.7.00 level. We identify three reasons for the resilience of USD/JPY versus implied fair value: 1) A narrowing negative USD risk premium; 2) Strong global risk sentiment despite a US economic slowdown; and 3) Speculative JPY short positioning amid low volatility during the summer season. That said, USD/JPY might drop significantly if risk sentiment worsens due to increasing concerns about a US economic slowdown. Worsening risk sentiment, led by concerns about a US economic slowdown, could reverse all three points above. As such, we maintain a short USD/JPY position given its attractive risk/reward. We note that the September 5 US employment report and the subsequent CES preliminary benchmark revision are key to watch.
Please add me to your distribution list.

Fed Chair Jerome Powell struck a balanced tone at the Jackson Hole Economic Policy Symposium. Whereas he had previously focused on the risk of inflation being prolonged by tariffs against a backdrop of labor market resilience, at Jackson Hole he emphasized "increasing downside risks" to the labor market, pointing to weakness in the July Employment Situation report as well as substantial downward revisions for May and June.

This change in the Fed's communications - along with speculation that core FRB board members could turn more dovish as a result of President Trump's attempt to remove a Federal Reserve governor - has caused the Fed's terminal rate to be repriced downwards.

The 'fair' level of USD/JPY implied by US terminal rate pricing has dropped to around 141 as a result of this repricing (i.e., expectations of deeper Fed rate cuts), thereby making the dollar look even 'richer' than before with the exchange rate having continued to hover around 147 throughout August (see Exhibit 1).

Factors contributing to this divergence from fair value would appear to include: 1) A narrowing of the USD negative risk premium; 2) Buoyant global risk sentiment; and 3) Speculative yen-short positions over the low-volatility summer period.

As we discussed in JPY: Dynamics Post Reciprocal Tariff Announcement, June 13, 2025, principal component analysis for daily movements in USD/G10 CCY pairs points to the first principal component being reflective of USD- side movements and the second of global risk sentiment (see Exhibit 2).
Exhibit 1: USD/JPY and fair value implied US terminal rate pricing
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 2: PC1 and PC2 for each G10 currency pair versus USD
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research; Note: PCA analysis was conducted against the daily change of G10 USD/CCY pairs with the data post reciprocal tariff announcement (April 2 to date).

With regard to the first point, whereas one might ordinarily expect interest rate differences to be a significant driver of USD performance, a significant 'decoupling' has in fact been seen since the April reciprocal tariff announcements.

In How Much Risk Premium Is in USD? August 12, 2025, our strategist colleagues pointed to a wider negative term premium being priced into USD as US political uncertainty in the wake of the reciprocal tariff announcements caused European investors holding substantial US assets to hike their FX hedge ratios (see Exhibit 3).
Exhibit 3: Estimated USD risk premium which cannot be explained by rate differentials
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 4: US labor market surprise versus Global Risk Demand Index (GRDIDX index)\*
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research; Note: "Global Risk Demand Index is a proprietary index of risk appetite. US Pat. No. 7,617,143.

However, this negative USD risk premium does appear to have been narrowing since the second half of July, which may be a reflection of the US having struck deals with many of its trading partners and political uncertainty meanwhile becoming more of a factor in Europe. In any case, this narrowing has effectively served to 'cancel out' downward
pressure on USD associated with the aforementioned downward repricing of the Fed's terminal rate.

With regard to the second point, although US labor market data have indeed deteriorated of late, global risk sentiment has continued to improve amid expectations of the Fed opting for an 'insurance' rate cut for reasons of risk management (see Exhibit 4). This is likely to have been a negative for JPY owing to its popularity as a funding currency.

Enhancing our fair value model for USD/JPY to include not only the market- implied Fed terminal rate but also our own Global Risk Demand Index (a yardstick for the degree of monetary accommodation), we currently obtain a level of around 143 or somewhat closer to where it is actually trading (see Exhibit 5).

Finally, with regard to the third point, the residual in our enhanced model â€“ which has been widening since late July â€“ may be largely attributable to demand for speculative JPY carry trades over the low- volatility summer period (see Exhibit 6).
Exhibit 5: USD/JPY and fair value implied by US terminal rate pricing and our Global Risk Demand Index
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 6: Vol-adjusted carry versus residual from fair value implied by US terminal rate pricing and our Global Risk Demand Index
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research

As we discussed in JPY: Reduced Fiscal Concerns, Reduced Speculative JPY Shorts, July 22, 2025, USD/JPY trading flows appear to have been dominated by pension fund rebalancing and overseas investors buying up Japanese assets during Asian trading hours but also by more speculative positioning during London and New York trading hours.
Since late July, USD/JPY has tended to fall gradually during (later) New York and Asian trading hours but then rally back after the London open (see Exhibit 7).

Price action during the London morning session is strongly correlated with the speculative positioning of leveraged investors, who have been skewing to the JPY- short side of late and as of last week had already turned net short (see Exhibit 8).

To summarize, it would appear that reasons for USD/JPY trading some distance above the 'fair' level consistent with the market- implied Fed terminal rate include a narrowing of the USD negative term premium, an improvement in risk sentiment, and speculative JPY shorting by leveraged investors amid the seasonal summer drop- off in volatility.
Exhibit 7: Cumulative intraday performance of USD/JPY by each time zone
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 8: Cumulative USD/JPY performance during London morning versus CFTC net JPY positioning held by leveraged funds
Source: CFTC, Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research

We accordingly see potential for USD/JPY to drop sharply if risk sentiment takes a turn for the worse and/or leveraged investors begin to unwind their JPY shorts. As we discussed in Enter JGB 10s30s Steepener and Short 30y JGB ASW, August 25, 2025, the first potential catalyst might be the September 5 US Employment Situation report and the subsequent CES preliminary benchmark revision.
As of now it would appear that markets remain optimistic that an 'insurance' rate cut from the Fed will be sufficient to prevent a major slowdown in the US economy.

A big jump in the employment rate might thus weigh heavily on risk sentiment by focusing greater attention on downside risks to the US growth outlook, with USD/JPY moving closer to fair value due to the aforementioned three points starting to work in the opposite direction and fair value itself perhaps also falling due to expectations of a lower Fed terminal rate.

We therefore consider risk/reward to be skewed towards declines in USD/JPY, with any upside liable to be outweighed by downside in the event of negative surprises in economic indicators. As such, we maintain short USD/JPY.
- Trade idea: Maintain short USD/JPY at 147.00 with a target of 135 and a revised stop of 151
